Employing “SPORTS TECHNIQUES” to counter “ASOCIAL VIOLENCE”.

A few key learning points about martial arts (especially grappling - be it BJJ or others):
1-Your opponent will not use “LETHAL WEAPONS” (or any kind for that matter), that are not made available to you in the first place.
2-Your opponent does not “INTEND TO KILL YOU”, (whether employing weapons or not) in order to win.
3-Your opponent is matched to your “SKILL LEVEL”, more or less.
4-Your opponent will most likely follow the rules and regulations set forth (martial art).

Now a few key points about “REAL LIFE VIOLENCE”:
1-The rules you play by are totally different than those of your opponent.
2-You care about the “MORAL, ETHICAL & LEGAL STANDPOINT”, your opponent most likely does not.
3-On the mats, once your opponent taps out, the fight ends and you shake hands, while in reality, they may be feigning compliance to deceive you.
4-The “PLUS ONE RULE”, your opponent may have a friend (or more) that you’re unaware of, who may have no compunction of killing you.
5-Whatever your “ASSUMPTIONS” about your opponent are, you’re probably mistaken.
6-You are using “PAIN OR LIMB INCAPACITATION” as a deterrent or a fight ender, while your opponent may have a higher pain tolerance than you’d imagined, let alone be on drugs.
7-What you think is their MLCOA (Most Likely Course Of Action) is probably not even remotely close to their MDCOA (Most Deadly COA), and you can almost be sure that they’ll go for the latter.

A more suitable approach would be applying the 5Ds:
De-Conflict
De-Escalate
Dis-Engage
Dis-Appear
Defend (as a last resort)

It was October 23, 1951, when Brazilian Jiu Jitsu founder Helio Gracie challenged the No. 1 Judoka, the legendary Masahiko Kimura, to a grappling match for world bragging rights and to prove that his new Brazilian art was superior to the Japanese art of Judo, from which BJJ was spawned.
The story of this famously historical event where Gracie competed against Kimura—the same man from which the devastating submission hold the “Kimura” got its name.
With almost 200,000 spectators in attendance for the fight in Brazil & giving up 80 lbs (36+ Kg) to Kimura, Gracie understood that this was going to be a very challenging match. Gracie was even told by Kimura that if he could survive for three minutes without giving up, that he should be declared the winner.
The fight was set for two, 10-minute rounds. It was nearly four minutes into the second round before Gracie was forced to quit, not by his own will, but by his corner who threw in the towel to prevent any further injury that was being dished out by the much larger and stronger Kimura.
This fight clearly showed the true effectiveness of BJJ in the fact that Gracie was able to survive against a battle tested, world class Judoka with a great weight and size advantage for so long. #bjj #jiujitsu #gracie #graciejiujitsu #graciebarra #grappling #judo #martialarts #bjjlifestyle #gjj #graciejiujitsu #brazilianjiujitsu #heliogracie #kimuragracie #bjjhistory #gracievs #jiujitsuparatodos #jiujitsubrasileiro #tatame #porrada #sambo #history #sportshistory #jiujiteiros #joerogan #ufc #adcc #blackbelt #repost

What do you think about modern day men? Let’s share in the comments

In the era of Alexander the Great, he conquered the world at the age of 25. 

Today, many 25-year-olds are consumed by negative comments on social media. 

But Alexander didn’t concern himself with others’ opinions because he knew his true identity. His resilience, dedication, and sense of purpose shaped his character.

In our modern world, men must also cultivate resilience. It doesn’t come naturally; it requires intentional training and choosing a purpose-driven lifestyle. 

As Bruce Lee wisely said, don’t pray for an easy life; pray for the strength to endure difficulties.

 It is through challenges that we develop true strength. If you opt for an easier path, you won’t experience the growth needed to become the best version of yourself. 

@ronintactics

Interview avec la légende Cheick KONGO. Dans cet interview il revient sur sa carrière, son passage à l’UFC et son combat incroyable face à Pat BARRY en 2011. Lors de notre échange il évoque sans langue de bois le dopage qui ravage le mma et comment il gangrène le sport. À 46 ans celui qui a côtoyer l’organisation de Dana WHITTE pendant 7 ans et 18 combats, nous donne son avis sur la nouvelle génération de combattants français présent dans l’organisation. Plus qu’un simple combattant celui qui attache un point d’ordre aux droits des combattants nous donne son avis sur Francis NGANNOU et son parcours exceptionnel. Cédric DOUMBÉ fait aujourd’hui de part ses performances et ses atouts d’orateurs parti des combattants uniques en leurs genre et Cheick KONGO l’a bien compris il nous donne ainsi son avis sur le personnage Cédric et le combattant. Ciryl GANE a toujours était un espoir du MMA français dans la quête d’une ceinture à l’UFC Cheick qui côtoie la même catégorie nous donne son avis sur la faisabilité ou non d’un couronnement. Enfin durant toutes ses années de combattant Cheick a tissé des liens fort avec Quinton rampage JACKSON qui est aujourd’hui son amis proche, il nous dévoile sans langue de bois la nature de ses rapports avec lui et l’origine de leurs amitié.
